                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Washington August 20&#47;88<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Sabato Morais LL. D.<lb/>
                President of the Faculty of the Jewish<lb/> Theological Seminary&#58;<lb/>
                Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I have the honor to render a<lb/> brief report of my first course of lectures in the<lb/> Seminary.  On July 1st the field covered by the sci&#45;<lb/>ence of Biblical Archaeology was outlined&#44; and at the<lb/> following meetings several topics were fully treated<lb/> for the purpose of illustrating the methods of re&#45;<lb/>search&#58; The Creation&#44; Paradise&#44; Deluge and Genea&#45;<lb/>logical table were discussed in detail&#44; the accounts<lb/> preserved in the Babylonian literature were pre&#45;<lb/>sented&#44; and other early statements were compared.<lb/>  Special stress was laid on Biblical Geography&#44; and<lb/> grammatical and linguistic questions were inci&#45;<lb/>dentally alluded to.  The course closed with a<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>resume of Assyrian History with special reference<lb/> to the period contemporary with the kings of Israel<lb/> and Judah.  As the study of the Bible must always<lb/> be the centre of a scientific Semitic training as<lb/> well as of a practical theological education&#44; and<lb/> as the discoveries on Hebrew&#44; Phoenician&#44; Assyrian and<lb/> Egyptian monuments have done much and <del>y</del> will<lb/> do yet more to confirm and elucidate the Bible<lb/> and cause it to stand out in clearer relief.  I<lb/> would respectfully suggest that&#44; as far as the cur&#45;<lb/>riculum will allow&#44; the course in Biblical Ar&#45;<lb/>chaeology be continued.<lb/></p>
            <p>Respectfully submitted<lb/>
                Cyrus Adler<lb/>
                Lecturer on Biblical Archaeology.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
